Applied Data Science Capstone - Bubble Tea Expansion¶

Shuaib Shameem¶

For my capstone project, I wanted to explore a business problem I could hypothetically encounter with my current business.

Business Problem¶

As a bubble tea restaurant owner, I am looking to expand my business to new locations. I have seen success from my current location in Schaumburg, IL, and am looking to open a new location in one of Chicago's communities. Which of Chicago's communities could yield similar success for a new location?

Project Aims¶

This project will use demographics and businesses to identify communities in Chicago which are similar to the original location.

def getNearbyVenues(names, latitudes, longitudes, radius=1500,LIMIT=100):
    i = 1
    venues_list=[]
    for name, lat, lng in zip(names, latitudes, longitudes):
        print(i, ': ', name)
        
        if name == 'Schaumburg':
            radius = 3300
        else:
            radius = 1500
        
        # create the API request URL
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            radius, 
            LIMIT)
            
        # make the GET request
        response_code = 500
        while response_code != 200:                #reattempt GET request if server returns an error
            request_got = requests.get(url)
            response_code = request_got.status_code
        
        
        results = request_got.json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
        
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue
        venues_list.append([(
            name, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            v['venue']['name'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
            v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])
        
        i = i+1

    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['Neighbourhood', 
                  'Neighbourhood Latitude', 
                  'Neighbourhood Longitude', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']
    
    return(nearby_venues)

In [108]:
def return_most_common_venues(row, num_top_venues):
    row_categories = row.iloc[1:]
    row_categories_sorted = row_categories.sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    return row_categories_sorted.index.values[0:num_top_venues]

num_top_venues = 10
indicators = ['st','nd','rd']

columns=['Neighbourhood']
for index in np.arange(num_top_venues):
    try:
        columns.append('{}{} Most Common Venue'.format(index+1, indicators[index]))
    except:
        columns.append('{}th Most Common Venue'.format(index+1))
        
chicago_venues_sorted = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns)
chicago_venues_sorted['Neighbourhood'] = chicago_grouped['Neighbourhood']

for index in np.arange(chicago_grouped.shape[0]):
    chicago_venues_sorted.iloc[index, 1:] = return_most_common_venues(chicago_grouped.iloc[index, :], num_top_venues)

Utilizing the Elbow Method to determine the most efficient number of clusters for K-Means

In [110]:
distortions = []
for i in range(1,20):
    km = KMeans(
        n_clusters = i, init='random',
        n_init=10, max_iter=300,
        random_state=0)
    km.fit(chicago_grouped.drop('Neighbourhood',1))
    distortions.append(km.inertia_)

distortions_2 = []

    km = KMeans(

        n_init=10, max_iter=300,
        random_state=0)
    km.fit(demo_clustering)
